# 🎯 Goals

> AutoForge Agents module enables spec-driven serial cooperation of profession-bearing AI agents, maximizing quality and token efficiency through relay orchestration.


## Goals

| ID | Goal | Priority | Status | Stakeholder |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| G1 | Agent Identity System supports Soul, Profession, and Model configuration per agent | P0 | Done | Tooling Team |
| G2 | Relay Orchestrator executes serial agent flows with baton passing and gate enforcement | P0 | Implemented | Tooling Team |
| G3 | Handoff Protocol compresses context between agents, achieving ~5× token savings vs parallel multi-agent | P0 | Implemented | Tooling Team |
| G4 | Checkpoint & Durability system enables long-running flows to survive crashes and resume without context loss | P0 | Implemented | Tooling Team |
| G5 | Token Budgeting tracks and enforces per-step spend with cost analytics visible in Agents view | P1 | Implemented | Tooling Team |
| G6 | Boss-first execution: GSD mode runs autonomously with optional Check mode for gate review | P0 | Done | Tooling Team |
| G7 | Spec pyramid supports Goals → Architecture → Designs → Plans → Tests → Reviews → Reports with no APIs category | P0 | Done | Tooling Team |
| G8 | Chat-First Gate Approval with Smart Secretary | P0 | Implemented | UI Team |
| G9 | Specs Workspace with Bidirectional Traceability | P0 | Implemented | UI Team |
| G10 | Live Relay Pipeline Visualization | P0 | Implemented | UI Team |
| G11 | Responsive and Accessible Frontend | P1 | Implemented | UI Team |

---

## G1 Agent Identity System supports Soul, Profession, and Model configuration per agent
**Status:** implemented
**Depends on:** G7

- [x] Agents can be defined with a Soul (markdown character definition)
- [x] Agents can be assigned a Profession that determines spec ownership, tools, and handoff rules
- [x] Agents can be configured with a Model (provider, model name, temperature, max_tokens)
- [x] Built-in professions exist: Assistant, Advisor, Architect, Planner, Coder, Tester, Reviewer, Documenter
- [x] Custom professions can be added via `.autoforge/professions/` YAML files

The Agent Identity separates *who the agent is* (Soul), *what it can do* (Profession), and *what cognitive substrate it uses* (Model). This enables fine-grained control over agent behavior and cost optimization through model tiering.

---

## G2 Relay Orchestrator executes serial agent flows with baton passing and gate enforcement
**Status:** implemented
**Depends on:** G1

- [x] Flow specs define ordered steps with professions, gates, loops, and branches
- [x] Only one agent holds the baton at any time
- [x] Orchestrator enforces tool availability per profession
- [x] Orchestrator routes handoffs deterministically without LLM coordination cost
- [x] Loop bounds and error routing prevent infinite cycles

The Orchestrator is pure deterministic code (Rust), not an LLM. It reads Flow specs, manages the Pipeline state machine, and routes batons. This eliminates token spend on coordination and makes routing predictable.

---

## G3 Handoff Protocol compresses context between agents, achieving ~5× token savings vs parallel multi-agent
**Status:** implemented
**Depends on:** G1, G2

- [x] Handoff documents exclude raw chat history
- [x] Handoff documents include: summary, decisions, open questions, spec updates, work product, context pointers
- [x] Context scoping filters specs to only those relevant to the receiving profession
- [x] Each agent receives ≤9k tokens at spawn (Soul + relevant Specs + Handoff)
- [x] Agents pull additional context on demand via tools, not via push

The Handoff Protocol is the core token-efficiency mechanism. By discarding chat history and summarizing work product, agents start each turn with minimal context. Parallel multi-agent systems suffer O(N×K) token overhead; relay reduces this to O(sum of scoped contexts).

---

## G4 Checkpoint & Durability system enables long-running flows to survive crashes and resume without context loss
**Status:** implemented
**Depends on:** G2, G3

- [x] Every handoff produces a checkpoint with: git state, ledger state, handoff document, file manifest, token usage
- [x] Runs can resume from any checkpoint after process restart
- [x] Resume rehydrates the next agent from checkpoint (no chat history restored)
- [x] Rollback restores files, ledger, and state to a previous checkpoint
- [x] Fork creates a new run from an existing checkpoint with different parameters

Since agents "work longer rather than quicker," flows may run for hours or days. Checkpointing makes this safe. On resume, the next agent starts fresh from the Handoff Document — token cost is identical to continuous execution.

---

## G5 Token Budgeting tracks and enforces per-step spend with cost analytics visible in Agents view
**Status:** implemented
**Depends on:** G2

- [x] Per-step token budgets with configurable limit, warning threshold, and strategy
- [x] Budget strategies: HardStop, EscalateModel, SummarizeContext, SkipOptional
- [x] Agents view shows real-time token spend and "savings vs parallel" estimates
- [x] Cumulative run budget prevents runaway costs
- [x] Cost analytics persist across checkpoints

Token budgeting makes cost a first-class constraint. The Agents view compares actual relay cost against estimated parallel-swarm cost to demonstrate savings.

---

## G6 Boss-first execution: GSD mode runs autonomously with optional Check mode for gate review
**Status:** implemented
**Depends on:** G2

- [x] RelayMode enum exists: `GSD` (default) and `Check`
- [x] GSD mode: only GoalGate requires human approval; Design, Plan, Execution gates are auto
- [x] Check mode: every gate pauses for human review
- [x] Reviewer acts as internal quality auditor in GSD mode (no human gate)
- [x] Documenter compiles and delivers final Report as boss-facing product
- [x] Boss is interrupted only on ambiguity, blockage, budget exceed, or explicit Check mode

The human is the boss, not a coworker. The default behavior is autonomous execution. The boss gives one order and receives a Report. Human gates are opt-in, not mandatory.

---

## G7 Spec pyramid supports Goals → Architecture → Designs → Plans → Tests → Reviews → Reports with no APIs category
**Status:** implemented
**Depends on:** G1

- [x] APIs category removed from spec system
- [x] Interface specs (REST endpoints, schemas) live in Designs under `Interface` section
- [x] Architect owns Designs (including interfaces), not a separate APIs category
- [x] Documenter generates public API docs as product, not spec
- [x] Reports are relay execution summaries (cost, confidence, deliverables)

Specs are internal decision records (how to build). Products are shipped artifacts (code + public docs). Interface contracts are design specs; public API docs are generated products.

## G8 Chat-First Gate Approval with Smart Secretary
**Status:** implemented
**Depends on:** G6, G7

The chat is the boss's office. All gates, regardless of origin, are delivered here. The secretary only enters when a signature is needed or the job is done.

